The Stage of May
London — — Facing the newly appointed British Prime Minister Theresa May is a daunting task: carrying out the electorate's demand — — or more accurately, the voters of England and Wales — — to "leave the EU" and managing the far-reaching consequences that this undertaking will bring.
The challenge she faces dwarfs those of her predecessors in recent years.
But she may have the capability to accomplish this task.
No one should underestimate May.
Like German Chancellor Merkel, who has already demonstrated courage in a series of crises, May has all the tools necessary to complete the task in her hands.
She is smart and resilient, and has no patience for nonsense.
She has a strong sense of public service and equally strong values.
Unbound by any ideology, she is very good at taking control, acting within self-imposed boundaries to ensure familiarity with the issues she handles.
May has won most of the battles she has been involved in, and is merciless to those who have treated her with underhanded tactics.
However, she has made few enemies within the party and is quite popular among ordinary members.
This is a powerful combination — she needs to fully utilize it to lead the UK's Brexit process.
The UK's Brexit process has definitely begun.
Even if Scotland and Northern Ireland voted to remain in the EU, May has repeatedly stated that the Brexit referendum cannot be reversed.
She has repeatedly said "Brexit means Brexit," and her ministers under her also support her view.
But May has not yet given a precise definition of Brexit.
This task is extremely difficult to accomplish.
Imagine someone telling you, "Breakfast is breakfast," and then starting to prepare food for you.
You would find it hard to clearly know exactly what you are going to eat.
A Northern Ireland "Ulster Fry"—eggs, bacon, sausage, black pudding, potatoes, soda bread, and fried tomatoes—with a cup of tea?
Coffee and pastries?
Depending on your environment and personal preferences, you might feel very differently about various possible combinations.
The same applies to Brexit.
Some people may primarily focus on preventing EU labor from entering the UK.
Others are more concerned about gaining access to the single market.
But unlike breakfast, Britain cannot order a full course of every dish on the menu.
The reality that Brexit supporters often ignore is that the EU will not give Britain benefits for free.
This is not because EU leaders want to win popularity or punish Britain for rejecting the EU (although such inflammatory rhetoric sometimes becomes rampant, for example, when the UK's new foreign secretary Boris Johnson referred to "Hitler-style imperialism").
On the contrary, we Britons often forget that everyone — including the EU and all its member states — has political or commercial interests that they are committed to protecting.
For May, the core challenge over the next few months will be to determine what Britain's goals should be, based on reality, after the tough negotiations on its relationship with the EU (which involves its relationship with the world in the trade area) begin.
Given the scope of the agenda (I can think of at least six major topics that would require separate negotiations), the negotiation process may take several years to complete.
(By the time the negotiations are completed, my 11-year-old granddaughter may already be starting university!
) We must clarify our priorities to prevent the negotiations from taking even longer.
The goal is obviously to achieve a balance between allowing British goods and services (especially financial services) to enter other European countries and restricting EU citizens from entering the UK.
The more negotiators gain in one area, the greater the concessions they need to make in other areas.
May needs to make full use of the knowledge, skills, and political capital she possesses to ensure the reasonableness of the negotiation deal.
But even if she succeeds in achieving her goal, she will still find that the dissatisfied are not just a part of them — this outcome is inevitable — but all of them.
This will exacerbate another major challenge facing the May government: narrowing the growing divide in British society exposed by Brexit.
The blue-collar workers in northern and central England were the main force behind the Brexit referendum, and they have always been alienated from political leaders, left behind by globalization, and marginalized by the so-called agents of globalization — the EU.
The metropolitan areas of England — especially London — may have benefited greatly from globalization, but they have not received any benefits.
Many members of the blue-collar working class ultimately fell prey to the promises of anti-establishment figures due to a lack of confidence in the Labour Party led by left-wing leader Jeremy Corbyn.
"We will reverse globalization," they said.
"We will drive out immigrants who suppress wages and transfer hundreds of millions of pounds that would have gone to the EU into public services."
They promised that leaving the EU would allow Britain to return to a safer and more prosperous past.
Leave campaigners cannot truly deliver on these promises.
Globalization cannot be reversed, nor can the immigration from the EU be cut off.
Any such measures would only destroy British businesses.
Even if economic downturns lead to a decrease in immigration, the workers who voted for Brexit may still be disheartened to find that low-paying jobs remain low-paying and the pressure on public services remains heavy.
This is unlikely to lead to an improvement in social cohesion.
The Brexit referendum has already triggered a populist sentiment storm that is difficult to control.
Just as Donald Trump has been unable to improve the situation of working-class American voters, regardless of how the circumstances may seem, Brexit also entirely fails to benefit those who chose it.
Despite its many advantages, such challenges may still be beyond May's ability to overcome.
